                      For the children, by the children                    Children in the city have one more reason to celebrate this summer holidays. For, beginning today, is a five-day theatre festival, specially for children, that promises to provide loads of fun, action, inspiration and entertainment. Performed by children, the festival will feature six plays that highlight issues of contemporary relevance pertaining to the young generation. It is produced by students of Nehru Childrens Museum under the direction of Ramaprasad Banik. The festival will be inaugurated this evening at 6 by mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharyya and city police commissioner Goutam Mohan Chakraborty. Besides, noted citizens of Calcutta, including well-known theatre personalities Usha Ganguli and Goutam Halder, will speak on this occasion. This will be followed by the staging of Bhanga Buker Panjore (a scene from the play appears here). A play that deals with the theme of loneliness in children, it lays bare certain uncomfortable truths about modern urban society. At the same time, it salutes the brave little warriors amongst us who rise above all odds to write their own destiny. To be followed by: May 26 - Mahavidya Primary (6.30 pm) and Jujur Jama (produced by Taki Natyam; 7.30 pm); May 27 - Ekla Pagal; May 28 - Saraswati Samipeshu and May 29 - Luxemburger Laxmi.                    Event: Childrens drama festival organised by Nehru Childrens Museum When: May 25 - 29; 6.30 pm onwards Where: Academy of Fine Arts	                    
